---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import { SITE } from "@/config";
import packageJson from "../../package.json";

const { dependencies, devDependencies, engines, version: themeVersion } = packageJson;

function cleanVersion(v: string | undefined): string {
  if (!v) return "—";
  return v.replace(/^[\^~>=<]+/, "");
}
---

<Layout
  title={`Blog Stack | ${SITE.title}`}
  description="The technology stack behind this blog: Astro, AstroPaper, Tailwind CSS, Pagefind, and how it all gets published."
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />
  <main id="main-content" class="app-layout pb-12">
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-semibold sm:text-3xl">About the Blog Stack</h1>

    <section class="app-prose mt-8">
      <h2>What powers this blog</h2>

      <p>
        This blog is a statically generated site — every page is pre-built at deploy time into plain HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. There is no server-side runtime, no database, and no CMS. The result is a site that is fast, secure, and cheap to host.
      </p>

      <p>
        The static site generator is <a href="https://astro.build/">Astro</a>, built on Node.js. Astro ships zero JavaScript to the browser by default, adding only what is explicitly needed. The visual theme is <a href="https://github.com/satnaing/astro-paper">AstroPaper</a>, adapted and extended for this site. Full-text search is handled by <a href="https://pagefind.app/">Pagefind</a>, which indexes the site at build time so search works with no backend. Hero images are processed at build time by <a href="https://sharp.pixelplumbing.com/">Sharp</a>, resizing and cropping to the right dimensions on every deploy.
      </p>

      <h2>Jekyll vs. Astro: Lighthouse comparison</h2>
      <p>
        Before migrating to Astro in January 2026, the site ran on Jekyll. These scores were measured across three matching posts on desktop, using Google Lighthouse. The Astro scores were captured from the staging environment before the production launch.
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Category</th>
            <th>Jekyll (avg)</th>
            <th>Astro (avg)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Performance</td>
            <td>57</td>
            <td>91</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Accessibility</td>
            <td>87</td>
            <td>94</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Best Practices</td>
            <td>73</td>
            <td>88</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>SEO</td>
            <td>100</td>
            <td>—*</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>
        <em>* Astro SEO scores were measured on the staging URL (<code>kyleskrinak.github.io/astro-blog/</code>), which has a non-canonical URL. The production site at <code>kyle.skrinak.com</code> scores comparably to Jekyll on SEO.</em>
      </p>

      <h2>Current versions</h2>
      <p>
        These versions are read directly from <code>package.json</code> at build time. They update automatically whenever a dependency is bumped — no manual maintenance required.
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Component</th>
            <th>Version</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><a href="https://astro.build/">Astro</a></td>
            <td>{cleanVersion(dependencies.astro)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><a href="https://github.com/satnaing/astro-paper">AstroPaper theme</a></td>
            <td>{themeVersion}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><a href="https://tailwindcss.com/">Tailwind CSS</a></td>
            <td>{cleanVersion(dependencies.tailwindcss)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><a href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/">TypeScript</a></td>
            <td>{cleanVersion(devDependencies.typescript)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><a href="https://pagefind.app/">Pagefind</a></td>
            <td>{cleanVersion(devDependencies.pagefind)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><a href="https://sharp.pixelplumbing.com/">Sharp</a></td>
            <td>{cleanVersion(dependencies.sharp)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Node.js (minimum)</td>
            <td>{engines.node}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>What makes it a great platform</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Zero server runtime.</strong> Every page is a static HTML file. There is nothing to patch, no runtime to exploit, and no server to go down under load.</li>
        <li><strong>Near-100 Lighthouse scores.</strong> Static HTML with minimal JavaScript loads fast by default. No client-side rendering, no layout shift from dynamic content.</li>
        <li><strong>Full-text search without a backend.</strong> Pagefind builds a search index at deploy time. Readers can search the entire archive without any API call to a server.</li>
        <li><strong>Automatic image optimization.</strong> Sharp resizes and crops every hero image at build time. Browsers receive the right size for their viewport — no oversized images shipped over the wire.</li>
        <li><strong>Dark mode.</strong> Theme toggle persists across sessions, respects system preference on first visit.</li>
        <li><strong>RSS feed.</strong> Full feed generated automatically at build time for every post.</li>
        <li><strong>Visual regression testing.</strong> <a href="https://playwright.dev/">Playwright</a> runs screenshot comparisons on every pull request to catch unintended layout changes before they reach production.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Infrastructure and how a post gets published</h2>

      <p>
        The blog is served from <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/s3/">AWS S3</a> behind <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/cloudfront/">Amazon CloudFront</a>, a global content delivery network. Static files are cheap to store and CloudFront caches them at edge locations worldwide.
      </p>

      <p>
        Every change flows through a three-branch gitflow before reaching production:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>develop</strong> — all work lands here first.</li>
        <li><strong>staging</strong> — a pull request from develop to staging triggers a <a href="https://github.com/features/actions">GitHub Actions</a> build pipeline that runs the full build, validates configuration, checks Disqus identifiers, and deploys the output to <a href="https://kyleskrinak.github.io">GitHub Pages</a>. This gives a live pre-production environment where the full site can be browsed before anything touches S3.</li>
        <li><strong>main</strong> — a pull request from staging to main triggers the production deploy: Astro build, S3 sync, and a CloudFront cache invalidation.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        No post reaches <a href="https://kyle.skrinak.com">kyle.skrinak.com</a> without first passing a review on <a href="https://kyleskrinak.github.io">GitHub Pages</a>. GitHub Actions handles all deployments — automated build, link checking, and visual regression tests run on every pull request.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>
